comments.body:
@cevich Well, we do need the container to remain running long enough for `top` to see it, so `true` probably isn't a good choice - it returns immediately.

This seems to be some sort of race. We make two containers in a pod with `podman run` which should not return until the containers have successfully started, then run `podman pod top` to check how many containers in the pod are running, and find only one container. We're reading the processes that are running via CGroups, so potentially they're slow to update running processes, or maybe the second container is just starting slow enough that we don't show it as running yet.

The easy solution, from @baude in his PR to fix the test, was to just add some sleeps between the run commands and pod stop, to give the system state time to settle.
